<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by the World Development Movement (WDM)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:20pt">EIS 20</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by the World Development Movement (WDM)</span></p></div><br style="clear:both; mso-break-type:section-break; page-break-before:auto" /><div><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">About the World Development Mo</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">vement</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The World Development Movement (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">WDM</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> campaigns against the root causes of poverty and inequality. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Working in solidarity with activists around the world, we oppose injustice and challenge the policies and institutions which keep poor people poor. We research and promote positive alternatives </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> put the rights of poor communities before the interests of big business. WDM is a democratic membership organisation of individuals and local groups. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">WDM’s ‘Carbon Capital’ campaign focuses on the role of the UK financ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ial</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> sector in bankrolling harmf</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ul fossil fuel extraction projects across the world.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> As such, our particular interest in this inquiry is the role played by UK financial institutions in extractive industries. In this submission we will focus on questions of relevance to this. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Executive Summary</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Fossil fuel extraction poses a grave threat to communities at the point of extraction as well as to the climate. Those implicated in harmful fossil fuel extraction projects are subject to serious reputational risks. These reputational risks extend to UK financial institutions, which are investing billions of pounds in fossil fuel projects across the world, and to the UK government, which has close political ties to these financial institutions. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Remaining a global centre for extractive industries threatens UK economic and business interests because of the threat of a so-called ‘carbon bubble’ brought on by ‘stranded’ fossil fuel assets. In contrast, there is a strong economic and business case for rapid investment in renewable energy, which has the potential to boost economic growth and create jobs. However, UK business interests are not the only criteria by which investment decisions ought to be made; the well-being of people and the environment must also be a priority. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In order to curb the harm caused by fossil fuel extraction to communities and the climate, extractive industries must be subject to tighter regulation. Regulating fossil fuel companies themselves is essential but insufficient; the UK government must also regulate UK financial institutions to drastically reduce their financing of fossil fuel projects across the world. In failing to regulate in this way, the UK is missing out on the chance to build a thriving renewables sector as has been created by regulatory incentives in many other countries. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Remaining a global centre for extractive industries runs counter to the economic, environmental and social interests of the UK. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In addition, the UK government must prioritise the interests of people in the global south, who are on the frontlines of fossil fuel extraction and climate change.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Recommendations </span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Mandatory Carbon Reporting to be extended to financed emissions. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The UK has recently passed regulations that mean that all quoted companies on the main market of the London Stock Exchange have to disclose their carbon emissions. However, the fact that this excludes indirect emissions caused by financial investments, means that banks and other financial institutions’ reported emissions are wildly inaccurate. The introduction of mandatory scope III emissions reporting would force banks and big institutional investors to face up to their true climate impact.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">More regulation to achieve greater transparency of banks lending and investment banking activities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. At the moment, researching the activities of banks is fraught with difficulty. Without access to expensive propriety databases, most people are currently unable to see what their bank is investing in. Banks need to be forced to disclose more about their specific investments in the fossil fuel sector.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Transparency of institutional investors' holdings of equity and debt securities in fossil fuel companies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. At the moment, pension funds, asset management firms and other institutional investors are not obliged to disclose information about their investments to the public, or even their own members. This state of affairs has to change to enable greater public scrutiny of the investment practices of the biggest investors.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Reform of listing criteria</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> At the moment, the UK's listing authority, the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) is charged only with ensuring that companies corporate governance and reporting meets certain standards before allowing them to list on the London Stock Exchange. Listing rules should be expanded to include social, environmental and climate criteria to prevent firms with dubious records from using London as a base to raise money for their destructive activities. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Response</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">What are the corporate governance concerns raised by the number of extractive industries companies listed in the UK? Are there reputational risks for the UK and UK financial institutions in being a centre for such businesses?</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">People across the world are already feeling the effects of climate change, which is being driven in part by fossil fuel extraction projects undertaken by companies that are financed by UK financial institutions. While climate change poses substantial risks to the UK, the world’s poorest countries are experiencing the most severe effects. People in the global south have done the least to cause climate change yet are the most severely impacted; this is a gross injustice. If action is not taken to avoid a six degree global temperature rise, the effects for humanity will be catastrophic.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Fossil fuel extraction projects also have devastating effects on local communities. People are often displaced from their land, or see the land, air and water they rely on polluted and their livelihoods destroyed. Pollution from fossil fuel extraction can cause severe health problems. Violence and repression are also often associated with extractive industries.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Coal, oil and gas projects are expanding across the world, often in countries and communities where many people have no access to electricity. But very often, corporate-led fossil fuel projects fail to increase energy access, instead producing energy for export or for use by multinational companies. Companies that make their decisions based solely on their financial return often don’t see it as cost effective to provide electricity to the poorest communities, or those living in rural areas. Yet these are often the people who lack access to electricity. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In sum, fossil fuel extraction poses a grave threat to local communities and the climate. This is a severe corporate governance concern and any governments, companies or </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">financial institutions implicated in harmful extractive industries are subject to very serious reputational risks. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Numerous public opinion polls have demonstrated the extent of public opinion against fossil fuel extraction and public concern about climate change. A recent Comres poll showed that 61 per cent of people in the UK believe that ‘the government is not green enough when it comes to energy policy’. Recent polling conducted by Cardiff and Nottingham University showed that 74 per cent of people in the UK are very or fairly concerned about climate change while 79 per cent want to see a reduction in fossil fuel usage over the next few decades.</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Those implicated in fossil fuel extraction risk being the subject of strong public disapproval. The reputational damage and adverse publicity suffered by BP around the Deepwater Horizon oil spillage and by Shell around oil conflict in the Niger Delta provide telling examples of the risks taken on by companies engaging in fossil fuel extraction projects. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">These issues of corporate governance and reputational damage extend to UK financial institutions. In spite of government targets to reduce the UK’s carbon emissions, the UK finance sector pours billions of pounds into coal, oil and gas extraction across the planet. Shares in fossil fuel companies are worth £900 billion on the London Stock Exchange. The top five UK banks underwrote £170 billion in bonds and share issues for fossil fuel companies between 2010 and 2012 – more than eleven times what the UK contributed in climate finance for developing countries in the same period.</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The heavy involvement of the UK financial sector in bankrolling fossil fuel extraction also presents reputational risks to the UK government. A web of close links exists between the UK government and the finance and energy industries. One third of ministers in the current government have links with these industries, whether through former employment, receipt of donations, or use of their influence in favour of particular companies. Meanwhile, executives at big finance and energy firms are often appointed to serve on government committees or regulatory bodies.</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Recommendations</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In order for the UK government to minimise reputational risk to themselves and UK financial institutions, we recommend that, as a first step, the UK government acts to increase transparency around the UK finance sector’s bankrolling of fossil fuel extraction. This includes:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">1. Mandatory Carbon Reporting to be extended to financed emissions. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The UK has recently passed regulations that mean that all quoted companies on the main market of the London Stock Exchange have to disclose their carbon emissions. However, the fact that this excludes indirect emissions caused by financial investments, means that the reported emissions of banks and other financial institutions are many times lower than the emissions they are actually responsible for. The introduction of mandatory scope III emissions reporting would force banks and big institutional investors to reveal their true climate impact. Recent WDM research revealed that when ‘financed emissions’ are included, the annual carbon footprint of the Royal Bank of Scotland in 2012 is up to 1,200 times the footprint reported by the bank under the Carbon Disclosure Project. We estimate that RBS’s true emissions are up to 911 million tonnes of CO2 equivalent, which is 18 times the entire annual carbon footprint of Scotland, and 1.6 times the footprint of the whole of the UK.</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2. Transparency of institutional investors' holdings of equity and debt securities in fossil fuel companies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. At the moment, pension funds, asset management firms and other institutional investors are not obliged to disclose information about their investments to the public, or even their own members. This must change to enable greater public scrutiny of the investment practices of the biggest investors.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">3. More regulation to achieve greater transparency of banks lending and investment banking activities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. At the moment, researching the activities of banks is fraught with difficulty. Without access to expensive propriety databases, most people are currently unable to see what their bank is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">investing in. Government needs to act to force banks to disclose more about their specific investments in the fossil fuel sector.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 17.85pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 20.19pt; padding-left:1.11pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">But while more transparency is needed, it is not enough.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">There must be a fundamental reorientation of the entire economy in order for the UK to reduce emissions by 80 per </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">cent by 2050. Where market based carbon trading schemes and voluntary codes of conduct have failed, it is time for a bold reappraisal of the basic assumptions that underlie the post-1980s world of blanket deregulation and the unfettered flow of global capital. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">4. Reform of listing criteria</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> is one example of a new regulatory measure</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that the government should introduce. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">At the moment, the UK's listing authority, the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) is charged only with ensuring that companies’ corporate governance and reporting meets certain standards before allowing them to list on the London Stock Exchange. Listing rules should be expanded to include social, environmental and climate criteria to prevent firms with dubious records from using London as a base to raise money for their destructive activities. </span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Does the UK have the skills base to remain a centre for the extractive industries and to ensure that UK based businesses benefit from potential future opportunities such as shale gas?</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Given the threats that fossil fuel extraction pose to communities across the world and the climate, the UK ought to be aiming to move away from being a centre for extractive industries and towards being a centre for clean, renewable energy. As such, WDM believe that this question – about UK businesses benefiting from extractive industries – is the wrong question to be asking. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In fact, remaining a centre for extractive industries also poses a serious threat to the UK’s long-term economic stability and business interests. This is because of the threat of a so-called ‘carbon bubble’, which results from the over-valuation of oil, coal and gas on stock markets. As noted above, shares in fossil fuels are worth around £900 billion on the stock exchange, and make up a quarter of all shares listed there. However, only a small proportion of the world’s remaining coal, oil and gas reserves can be burnt before runaway climate change becomes unavoidable. Governments therefore need to restrict the amount of carbon that can be burned. What this means is that the fossil fuel assets of UK financial institutions (i.e. the investments that these institutions have in extractive industries) will become ‘stranded assets’. The economy is dependent upon investment in fossil fuels, which simply cannot be burned. Analysts predict that if the UK maintains its dependency on fossil fuels, another major financial crisis is inevitable.</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In contrast, there is a strong economic and business case for rapid investment in renewable energy. At present, green industry is one of few thriving sectors in the UK’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">faltering economy. The CBI estimate that over one third of the UK’s economic growth in 2011/2012 was from green business. They estimate that low-carbon technology could boost UK GDP by almost £20bn in 2014/2015.</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> There is the potential for the creation of over one million jobs in the transition towards a climate-friendly economy.</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The UK would be foolish to miss this opportunity to boost the UK economy while at the same time bringing greenhouse gas emissions under control.  However, the potential for UK business is not the sole criteria by which investment decisions should be made. Investing in renewable energy instead of fossil fuels not only makes better economic sense but, crucially, makes more sense for the well-being of people across the world and our environment. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Would increased regulation for London listed extractives companies result in competition from elsewhere or can it be used to make the UK a centre of excellence for best practice and corporate governance? </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Increased regulation for London listed extractives companies is essential to curb the destruction being caused by fossil fuels to local communities at the point of extraction and we have no option but to regulate fossil fuel extraction in order to avoid runaway climate change. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">However, regulating London listed extractives companies is insufficient; we must also regulate the UK financial sector to curb its financing of fossil fuel extraction. The UK government needs to give up the idea that the interests of the financial sector trump everyone else’s. This logic, which underpinned the financial crisis, is also driving runaway climate change, as UK financial institutions pour billions of pounds into coal, oil and gas projects across the world. In order to meet its own commitment of reducing carbon emissions by 80 per cent by 2050, the UK government must regulate to stop financial institutions bankrolling fossil fuels. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In failing to regulate in this way, the UK is missing out on the opportunity to create a thriving renewables sector. In contrast, the renewables sector in California, China, Demark, Germany and Spain has taken root from a mix of favourable regulation, including feed-in tariffs and other subsidies that include small-scale producers, renewables targets and infant industry protection. The UK is lagging behind other countries in the transition to a high-tech low-carbon energy system and economy. Increased regulation for extractives companies and financial institutions is one of the first steps we need to take to make a start on this transition. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">What is the competitive landscape for the extractive industries in the 21</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:8pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold; vertical-align:super">st</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> Century and is it in the UK’s interest to remain a global centre for them?</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">As outlined in paragraph 24, analysts suggest that a potential ‘carbon bubble’ poses a serious threat to the UK’s economic stability. In contrast, as outlined in paragraph 25, rapid investment in renewable energy has the potential to boost economic growth and create jobs. It is not, therefore, in the UK’s economic or business interests to keep gambling our economy on fossil fuels. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Furthermore, the UK is not insulated from the threat of runaway climate change. The UK government’s 2012 Climate Change Risk Assessment identifies risks several risks posed by climate change to the UK, including risks to agriculture, business, health and wellbeing, buildings and infrastructure, and natural environment.</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Climate change will continue to have increasingly severe social impacts in the UK, particularly for the most vulnerable.</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Remaining a global centre for the extractive industries as opposed to becoming a centre for clean, renewable industries is not in the UK’s interests on account of the threat posed by climate change to people in the UK. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Finally, the Committee on Climate Change, independent advisors to the government, argue that a rapid shift to low-carbon energy would prevent massive increases in fuel </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">bills for UK households over coming decades.</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In prioritising the interests of extractive industries over cleaner, cheaper renewable industries, the government is consigning UK households to decades of spiralling energy bills and fuel poverty. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Remaining</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> a global centre for the extractive inte</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rests runs counter to the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">UK’s interests in economic terms, in environmental terms and in social terms. Ho</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">wever, the UK government must also prioritise the interests of people in the global south, who are on the frontlines </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of the impacts </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of fossil fuel ext</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">raction and climate change. The impact of extractive industries on the world’s poorest is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">often </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">catastrophic. The UK government must take urgent action to give up its status as a global centre for extractive industries, starting with forcing UK financial i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nstitutions to be transparent a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">bout their scope III emissions.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">But while more transparency is needed, it is not enough. Only radical regulatory reform and a fundamental reorientation of the working of the financial sector will truly turn the system away from its dependency on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">fossil fuels</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. Indeed, there needs to be a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">fundamental reorientation of the entire economy in order for the UK to reduce emissions by 80 per cent by 2050. Where market based carbon trading schemes and voluntary codes of conduct have failed, it is time for a bold reappraisal of the basic assumptions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that underlie the post-1980s world of blanket deregulation and the unfettered flow of global capital. Such fundamental change requires more than a few specific policy solutions can provide. Nevertheless, steps should be taken now to tighten the regulatory</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> framework and disincentivise high carbon investment.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">23 September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Reyes, O (2013), </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Carbon capital: How the City bankrolls climate change</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. London. World Develoment Movement. March 2013. Available at:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><a href="http://www.wdm.org.uk/sites/default/files/Carbon_Capital_web.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.wdm.org.uk/sites/default/files/Carbon_Capital_web.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> On the risks posed by climate change to the UK, see:  HM Government (2012), </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">UK Climate Change Risk Assesment: Government Report.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> London: The Stationary Office. January 2012. Available at:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/69487/pb13698-climate-risk-assessment.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/69487/pb13698-climate-risk-assessment.pdf</span></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. On the disproportionate risks posed to countries in the global south, see: Jones, T and Edwards, S (2009), </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The climate debt crisis: why paying our dues is essential for tackling climate change. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">London. World Development Movement. November 2009. Available at: </span><a href="http://www.wdm.org.uk/sites/default/files/climatedebtcrisis06112009_0.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.wdm.org.uk/sites/default/files/climatedebtcrisis06112009_0.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name=